#### Part 1: Add Order Item Customization Controls

Each item on the menu should have a customization screen which displays controls for the customizable attributes of the order item. The controls should be appropriate for what they are responsible for changing (i.e. Buttons, Selection drop-downs, Radio buttons, checkboxes). Use the controls that make sense to you.

You may optionally combine IOrderItems into a single customization UserControl, but if you choose to do this, you need to be diligent to ensure only the controls that relate to the current item are shown. Such that we do not see the FlavorSelection for the Sailor Soda in the Warrior Water.

#### Part 2: INotifyPropertyChanged Implementation

For the changes to the item to appear in receipt, which we will implement in the next milestone, you need to implement the INotifyPropertyChanged interface in all menu item classes.

```csharp
/* Let's do an example here */

/* Consider the general drink class, all drinks have the Ice property. If we update the Ice property i.e. change the value from true to false or from false to true we need to notify that the Ice property has changed 

We can accomplish this with the following line of code
*/

PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, new PropertyChangedEventArgs("Ice"));

/* Remember when some properties change, it will require you to notify multiple different attributes. Think about what changes when you update the Size of a drink! */
```

#### Part 3: Test what you added

The easiest way to test whether a property was notified is to use the Assert.PropertyChanged method. Here is an example of what this looks like when we test that changing the Ice property notifies Ice.

```csharp
[Fact]
public void ChangingIceNotifiesIceProperty()
{
    var AJ = new AretinoAppleJuice();

    Assert.PropertyChanged(AJ, "Ice", () =>
    {
        AJ.Ice = true;
    });

    Assert.PropertyChanged(AJ, "Ice", () =>
    {
        AJ.Ice = false;
    });
}
```
